{
  "doc_id": "7939",
  "text": "Activation of T-cells by antigen leads to the production of cytokines, which in turn mediate downstream effector responses [CITATION_1] . Of the cytokines secreted, IFNγ is one of the best studied, having been shown to be a robust marker of T cell activation with levels correlating with the efficacy of the immune response [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . As a result, the detection of intracellular or secreted IFNγ has become an accepted surrogate for functional immune responses to antigen in many circumstances. Of the techniques available to measure IFNγ, ELISpot analyses are one of the most widely used due to their low cost, reliability and high sensitivity for detecting low numbers of antigen-specific cells [CITATION_4] . However, these assays require purified PBMCs and relatively large volumes of blood to perform.",
